Ce que je dis à mes amis non-américains
CAMBRIDGE – I travel frequently abroad and my foreign friends ask me each time, with varying degrees of bewilderment: but what is going on in your country?
Here is what I tell them.
First, be careful not to misunderstand the 2016 elections.
Unlike some comments, the American political system has not been swept away by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against elites.
Donald Trump exploited the vein of a tradition associated with leaders such as Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
And yet, Trump fell short of winning the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the elections by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand more votes had been cast differently in these states, Trump would have lost the Electoral College and the presidency.
Nevertheless, Trump's victory raises the real issue of rising social and regional inequalities in the United States.
J.D. Vance's latest bestseller, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the huge difference between California and the Appalachian region.
The research conducted by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among low-income White Americans without college degrees are worse than those of African Americans, who historically were at the bottom of inequality.
In 1999, the mortality rates among Whites without college education were around 30% below those of African Americans; by 2015, they were 30% higher.
Moreover, employment in industry, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for working-class Whites, has fallen significantly over the last generation, to only 2% of the workforce.
The former Democratic voters were seduced by Trump's promises to shake things up and bring jobs back to industry.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation risk making their lives even harder.
The second thing I tell my foreign friends is that you must not underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his rages on Twitter and his scandalous contempt for facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success is to monopolize the attention of viewers, and that the best way to do this is to make extreme statements without caring about the truth.
Twitter allows him to set his agenda and distract his critics.
What annoys commentators in the media and academia does not bother his supporters.
But as soon as he moves from his ongoing self-centered campaign to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that discourages some allies he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Typically, a president who fails to win the popular vote moves toward the political center to attract more support.
This is what George W. Bush did successfully in 2001.
On the other hand, Trump proclaims that he won the popular vote and acts as if it really was the case, pleasing his base voters.
Although Trump made strong centrist nominations to the Department of Defense, State, and National Security, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services sit at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His White House staff is divided between ideologues and pragmatists - and he intends to satisfy both camps.
Fourthly, one must not underestimate American institutions.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling and ask me if Trump is as dangerous a narcissist as Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
The United States, despite its many problems, is not Italy in 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but the founders of America were just as divided.
In the design of the US Constitution, the founders' goal was not to ensure government harmony, but to limit political power through a system of checks and balances that makes it difficult to exercise those powers.
A joke on this subject says that the founders created a political system such that it is impossible for King George to reign over us - impossible for him or for anyone.
Ineffectiveness has been put to the service of freedom.
The presidency of Trump is still in its early days and we cannot be certain what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
However, so far, the courts, Congress, and the states have upheld this balance of powers within the administration according to Madison's wishes.
And permanent executive department officials still carry weight.
Finally, my friends wonder what all this means for American foreign policy and for the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Honestly, I don't know, but I worry less about China's rise than about Trump's.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about free riders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing important global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and the management of our planet's common resources.
Despite problems with the international order under U.S. leadership, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
But no one can assert with certainty that this will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational issues.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first major party candidate in 70 years to question the American alliance system.
Since taking office in January, Trump's statements and those of his team suggest that he may persist.
After all, the power to constrain and convince the United States comes largely from having 60 allies (whereas China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's common goods, is more uncertain.
The director of Trump's Budget speaks of a budget of constraint power, with cuts made to the State Department and the United Nations system.
Other government members argue for replacing multilateral trade agreements with "fair and balanced" bilateral arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I tell my friends that I would like to be able to reassure them about these issues.
But I cannot.
